<H3> <TI>   Joint Control Point Set Up Near Mostar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803173094 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] A joint control point was set up at the southern 
approaches to Mostar this afternoon, at which UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] members are accompanied by HVO [Croatian 
Defense Council] policemen and members of the Bosnian Muslim 
army. Zdenko Vranjes reports for Croatian radio: 
  [Vranjes] This is the beginning of the implementation of the 
agreement signed yesterday between the commissions of the HVO 
and the Bosnia-Herzegovina army on setting up joint control 
points on the roads crossing the front lines. 
  Representatives of both sides signed maps yesterday with 
precisely outlined demarcation lines between the HVO and the 
Muslim forces. It was also agreed that six main roads be opened 
with unrestricted movement for all civilians, except for men 
between the ages of 16 and 60. It was also agreed that the 
following roads be opened: Zenica-Stari Vitez, 
Mostar-Jablanica-Konjic-Sarajevo, Kiseljak-Vares, 
Kiseljak-Busovaca, Prozor-Jablanica-Gornji Vakuf- Travnik, and 
Vitez-Zenica-Maglaj. 
  According to the Spanish UNPROFOR battalion, the HVO and the 
Muslim army have withdrawn their heavy weapons. Mortars have 
been withdrawn 10 kms and tanks and heavy guns 20 kms from the 
front line. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

