<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic `Pleading' to Kinkel on Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803203494 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1900 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We have just received the letter sent by the 
president of our country's Presidency Alija Izetbegovic to 
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel. It reads as follows: 
  Dear Sir: 
  In connection with your government's decision to deny 
further 
hospitality to the citizens of the so-called Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia, we wish to draw your attention to the fact that its 
literal implementation could do a great injustice to certain 
members of our nation. Namely, this decision also applies to 
Muslim refugees from Sandzak who, as your excellency knows all 
too well, have been the target of brutal repression by the 
Belgrade regime. Those from Sandzak had to flee their homes due 
to open police terror and also because they refused to be 
mobilized by the Serbian army and to be forced to commit crimes 
against the Croats and later against their brethren in Bosnia. 
To our knowledge, most of these people in Germany today hail 
from the municipalities of Novi Pazar, Sjenica, Tutin, Rozaje, 
Bijelo Polje, Berane, Prijepolje, Priboj, Nova Varos, Plevlja, 
and Plav. 
  I am pleading with you, Sir, to exempt these unfortunate 
people from the decision on deportation, because they simply 
have nowhere to return. They would be sent to prison or, worse, 
to the front in Bosnia or Croatia the minute they crossed the 
border, President Izetbegovic wrote in his letter to Klaus 
Kinkel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

