<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic on Consequences of Airspace Violations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803210694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2005 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, 8 Mar (TANJUG) -- "During the period 20-25 
February, NATO planes violated the airspace of the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY] on several occasions, threatening 
its sovereignty and territorial integrity, with possible 
unforeseeable consequences," Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav 
Jovanovic says in a letter forwarded to UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali on Tuesday. 
  Jovanovic draws the secretary general's attention to the 
fact 
that the airspace violations took place in the area of Boka 
Kotorska and near Uzice and Kraljevo, and said this was an 
integral part of a campaign of continuous pressure on the Serb 
nation. 
  "We are particularly concerned because all this is happening 
under the auspices of the United Nations and because nothing has 
been done yet to stop such provocations," the letter says. "If 
these violations continue they could spark off incidents with 
unforeseeable consequences for the security of not only the FRY 
but also the entire Balkan region, including the peace process 
aimed at ending the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina." 
  Jovanovic appealed to Butrus-Ghali to take appropriate 
measures within the framework of the United Nations and NATO to 
prevent "such dangerous provocations" in the future. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

