<H3> <TI>   German Official Defends Deportation Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0803162094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0803162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We have just received the following statement from 
the Ministry of Foreign Affairs: 
  The charge d'affairs of the German Embassy in Belgrade was 
summoned to the Federal Ministry today. He was asked to explain 
the German Government's decision on the mass deportation of 
Yugoslav citizens from Germany. 
  The German charge d'affairs stressed that the media reports 
on the expulsion of a large number of people were unfounded, 
that the number of the so-called asylum-seekers was not so 
large, and that deportation measures would be applied only 
against those who are in Germany illegally. 
  The German charge d'affairs was told that the method 
announced to deport the Yugoslavs is not acceptable, that it 
would represent the violation of human rights and international 
conventions, and that the deportation measures have been adopted 
in a discriminatory fashion without prior consultations with the 
Government of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia on solving 
complex humanitarian problems. The Federal Government has taken 
certain steps with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees with 
regard to this issue. 

</TEXT>

