<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Corridors Reopen for FYROM, Slovene Planes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903120794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1126 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 9 (TANJUG) -- Airlines from The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] and Slovenia will 
again use air corridors over the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia 
(F.R.Y.), after they announced settling of their dues over which 
the Belgrade flight control denied to provide them with its 
services as of March 1. 
  "The ban on flights over the F.R.Y. is still in force for 
some Turkish airlines, but the talks are underway and we hope 
the matter will be resolved to mutual satisfaction," said Branko 
Bilbija, the director of the Federal Flight Control Office. 
  He said that several national airlines tried to avoid paying 
the office's service fees by invoking international sanctions 
against the F.R.Y. 
  In the overall debt of millions of dollars incurred to the 
Federal Flight Control Office, Macedonia's share is said to 
amount to 2.5 million dollars. 
  Bilbija underscored that no U.N. Security Council's 
resolution banned flying through the F.R.Y. airspace, using or 
paying for the services of the Belgrade flight control. 
  He said that charging the airlines for their services was 
the 
only source of the office's income, which they spend on 
equipment and wages. Owing to that, he added, they maintained 
very high technical, technological and security standards. 
  The Federal Flight Control Office report said that during 
1993, 150,000 aircraft owned by 150 world airlines had used the 
F.R.Y. air routes. 
  In May 1992, the U.N. Security Council banned international 
flights of the Yugoslav JAT Airlines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

