<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac `Sharply' Criticizes Meciar in Assembly </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903131194 Prague CTK in English 1216 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0903131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava March 9 (CTK) -- Slovak President Michal 
Kovac sharply criticised Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar in 
parliament on Wednesday [9 March], accusing Meciar of an attempt 
to dismiss him. Kovac appeared in parliament today with a 
report on the state of the Slovak Republic. 
  "I had and still have nothing against the (ruling Movement 
for a Democratic Slovakia of which Meciar is chairman) HZDS and 
the government, but I have serious reservations about the way 
Mr. Meciar governs the country and the practices which create an 
atmosphere of confrontation in political life," Kovac said. He 
stated that at HZDS meetings he was regularly accused of 
"banding together" with the opposition and Hungarians, and of 
"being bribed" by foreign countries. 
  The end of Kovac's address seemed to be a defence of his 
performance as president and an extraordinarily strong criticism 
of the premier's methods of ruling. However, Kovac did not call 
on the parliament, in which the government has lost its 
majority, to dismiss the premier, nor did he urge the premier 
himself to resign. He said that an end should be put to 
denouncing people, and called for political, national and civic 
conciliation. 
  The premier was not present in parliament when Kovac was 
speaking. 
  Kovac assured deputies he would never commit treason "even 
if 
he had to drain the cup of bitterness to the dregs." 
  Observers believe the president's speech could influence 
talks between Meciar's HZDS and the Democratic Left Party (SDL), 
the strongest opposition party, on the government's stability, 
the term of early elections, if they take place, and the 
possibility of expanding the government coalition (now formed by 
the HZDS and the Slovak National Party -- SNS). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

