<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alliance of Democrats Asks Government To Resign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0603180194 Prague CTK in English 1348 GMT 6 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0603180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 5 (CTK) -- A call to the 
"democratic forces in the Slovak Parliament" was adopted by the 
opposition Alliance of Slovak Democrats (AD SR) at its meeting 
in Trebisov, east Slovakia. 
  The AD SR, headed by former Foreign Minister Milan Knazko, 
former aide of Premier Vladimir Meciar and currently his radical 
opponent, called on the opposition to make another attempt to 
pass the constitutional law on early elections. 
  Two recent attempts failed as it was not able to obtain the 
90 votes necessary for this. 
  "The political crisis in Slovakia is intensifying, while the 
latest steps by the governing forces are jeopardising the 
long-term economic and political interests of the country," says 
the appeal by the leadership of the AD SR which has eight 
deputies in the 150-member Slovak Parliament. 
  The AD SR considers the referendum on the the loss of 
mandates of the deputies who left their parties during the 
electoral term to be unconstitutional. 
  The AD SR call assured that if the current government is 
dismissed, it would support a broad coalition government which 
would lead Slovakia to the early elections which should be held, 
according to the AD SR, in autumn. 

</TEXT>

