<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Involvement in Seeking Settlement Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903162194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1430 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item by Stevan Cordas] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 9 (TANJUG) -- Americans have 
invested all their political credibility in finding a 
comprehensive settlement to the conflict in the war-torn former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina after their own 
prescription. 
  Judging by the U.S. President's special envoy Charles 
Redman's visit to Belgrade on Tuesday, the Americans seem to be 
very anxious to find the solution, but, at the moment, they fail 
to come up with a clear conception of how to give a definite 
shape to the peace package. 
  The reason for the U.S. anxiousness is obviously a result of 
its wish to neutralize, as efficiently as possible, the Russian 
initiative in seeking a solution to the Bosnian conflict. 
  Following the talks with Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic, Redman indicated two phases of the peace process. He 
said that the first phase, which was almost finished, would 
complete a Moslem-Croat deal on setting up a federation made up 
of territories controlled by the two peoples and its later 
entering into a confederation with Croatia. The key to the 
solution, however, could not be found before reaching the 
following (second) phase, for which the U.S. needs the 
participation of the third warring nation, i.e., the Serbs. 
  Redman's visit to Belgrade was a "feel the pulse" operation 
and an attempt to solve essential matters "in passing." It is 
hard to tell whether the U.S. official, while conferring with 
Milosevic and later with Bosnian Serb Republic Vice-President 
Nikola Koljevic, had found out what he came to Belgrade for. It 
was made clear to him, however, that the Moslem-Croat agreement 
is not binding for the Serb side. 
  Redman in Belgrade insisted on "an overall settlement" of 
the 
Bosnian crisis, but failed to specify what exactly he meant by 
that. He was also told that under the circumstances it was very 
hard for the Bosnian Serbs to take an integral stand. 
  The statements he made in Belgrade differ a great deal from 
a 
statement by U.S. Ambassador to Croatia Peter Galbraith. 
Redman, for instance, categorically argued that the 
Moslem-Croat agreement was not aimed against the Bosnian Serbs. 
On the other hand, Galbraith on Tuesday told the press 
conference in Zagreb the agreement's main aim was to put an end 
to the senseless conflict between the two nations, victims of 
the Serb aggression. 
  At a point when Redman tried to persuade the Bosnian Serbs 
of 
the necessity of their involvement in the latest peace process, 
Galbraith has offered them only an alternative -- either to join 
the Moslem-Croat agreement and the West, or to continue the war. 
  Be that as it may, Charles Redman left unfinished the job he 
came to Belgrade for, so he is likely to come back for talks 
shortly. 
  Meanwhile, the Russians don't sit on their hands, either. 
Bosnian Moslem Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic and Croatian 
Foreign Minister Mate Granic were in Moscow on Wednesday. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and U.S. State 
Secretary Warren Christopher are scheduled to meet next Monday. 
To all appearances, the situation would somewhat clear up only 
after all these talks about the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8422 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu047_y_94002" </HT>


