<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Leaders Try To Prevent Voting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1003095294 Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA in Romanian 8 Mar 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> AU1003095294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMANIA LIBERA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Elena Tomulescu: "The 14th Army Started </F>
Reprisals Against Those Who Participated in Poll in the Republic 
of Moldova"] 
  [Text] On the occasion of the sociological poll "What 
People Advise," Dniester leader Smirnov's police closed the 
border crossing point at Gura Bacului, while in Dubasari the 
military control of Romanians who wished to go to the polls was 
intensified. The 14th Army took steps to find out who were the 
people who had voted in the parliamentary elections and the 
referendum,. The employees of the Ministry of Interior of the 
Republic of Moldova did not have the right to vote in the 
referendum, just as the they did not have the right to vote in 
the parliamentary elections either. As far as the results of the 
referendum are concerned, all the international observers 
announced that there was a much reduced presence at the polls in 
case of the referendum polls than in the parliamentary 
elections, and the government-backed television of the republic 
announced a presence of over 70 percent at the polls. Just as 
it has always been the case so far, the population was used to 
explain the prosoviet policy promoted by President Snegur. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

