<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Rejects Broad Coalition Government Notion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903194394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0903194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1730 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The cross-party standing committee of all Slovak 
parliamentary parties met today shortly before 1700. President 
Michal Kovac and Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar were also 
present. Peter Weiss, the parliament's deputy speaker, has 
informed us about the meeting's results: 
  [Begin Weiss recording] The cross-party standing committee 
has met on my initiative. I based it on the final part of the 
president's speech on the need to seek ways toward national and 
political conciliation, healing political wounds, easing the 
atmosphere of confrontation, and creating peaceful conditions 
for early elections. 
  On the basis of this initiative, a meeting was held in the 
presence of both the president and the prime minister. 
Representatives of all parliamentary parties and movements were 
there. Various proposals were presented there for the creation 
of a broad coalition government--also by the president and 
myself. 
  It must be said that the prime minister explicitly rejected 
the idea of a broad coalition government until early elections 
are held. The atmosphere that arose there was more likely to 
lead to a new confrontation than to a constructive dialogue. 
That is, the prime minister showed unwillingness to seek a 
solution that would be generally acceptable. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

