<H3> <TI>   Refuses To Address Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903201694 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1830 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0903201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar took his 
place in parliament today during the discussion of Deputy 
Pittner's proposal to take a vote of no confidence in the Slovak 
Republic Government. 
  Pavol Kanis, from the Party of the Democratic Left, asked 
the 
prime minister to address parliament. 
  [Begin Meciar recording] Esteemed ladies and gentlemen, 
esteemed Mr. Speaker. I am pleased to take the opportunity 
given to me by parliament to speak. This did not use to be the 
habit in these rooms in the past. 
  I have, however, been unable to acquaint myself with the 
speech by the president. I was receiving the World Jewish 
Congress's delegation during his address. There is no written 
record (?of his speech). The government members were acquainted 
with the speech. I was, unfortunately, present at the 
discussion (?here in the back of this hall), and, hence, I 
missed the government session. I do not even have the papers 
that the government has. 
  I would consider it an honor to speak about these matters 
tomorrow. But do not ask me to speak today. I am not familiar 
with the issue on which I am to express an opinion. [end 
recording] 
  [Announcer] We are ready to broadcast the prime minister's 
speech in a live relay on ST2 tomorrow. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

