<H3> <TI>   Belgian Senators Focus on Hungarian Minority </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803191894 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0803191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] [Announcer] After yesterday's talks in 
Bratislava with Slovak Defense Minister Imrich Andrejcak, 
senators of the Kingdom of Belgium who are here at his 
invitation, visited southern Slovakia today. Peter Rohac has 
more to say about their agenda today. 
  [Rohac] [passage omitted] Although both senators are experts 
in defense and foreign policy, they also have great experience 
in the working of autonomy and coexistence between citizens of 
different ethnic backgrounds from their own country. [passage 
omitted] 
  On the other hand, Peter (Baby), a deputy for the municipal 
council, expressed the view that the local Hungarians, although 
Slovak Republic citizens, belonged to the Hungarian nation, 
which was artificially divided. 
  He alleged that the present Slovak state power was trying to 
assimilate the Hungarians rather than integrate them into a 
unified Slovak Republic. Our other state administration 
representatives reacted against this opposition standpoint. 
Senator Nestor Hubert Pecriaux, who is a member of the Council 
of Europe, remarked that they knew about the Hungarian political 
parties' complaints, but there was no need to dramatize the 
ethnic minority problem. On the basis of their experience here 
[in Slovakia], he thought that all who wanted to coexist could 
prove that this was possible. It is apparently clear that all of 
the European communities have a different approach to these 
questions, and it is logical that everybody has the right to 
organize himself according to how he feels, but, on one 
condition, and that is that all voters and citizens are 
satisfied. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

