<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Srpska Official Calls for New Peace Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903141694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1231 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0903141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 9 Mar (TANJUG) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, the 
president of the Assembly of the Srpska republic, said today 
that by first offering a draft solution on the basis of the 
Owen-Stoltenberg plan and then failing to meet its obligations 
from the draft, the European Union had wasted its chances of 
playing a more active role in the Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis. 
  The Serbs were asked to agree on 33.3 percent of the 
territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina for the Muslims; to allow 
the replacement of the Canadian battalion in Srebrenica; to 
withdraw heavy weapons from around Sarajevo; and to allow the 
opening of Tuzla airport, while in return the EU would do its 
utmost to ensure that the sanctions imposed on the Serb people 
were lifted as a matter of urgency, Krajisnik told Jagodina 
Radio today. 
  We have met all our commitments but the EU has done nothing 
to lift the sanctions. The EU alone is to be blamed for losing 
our trust and its reputation, and from now on any EU proposal 
will be met with a large amount of reservation, Krajisnik said. 
  On the other hand, Washington's proposal for a federation 
and 
confederation of Muslims and Croats and speculations about the 
Serbs joining the Muslim-Croat agreement indicate, to say the 
least, an inability to view the situation on the ground 
realistically, Krajisnik said, and went on to add: 
  It is only by pressure that a federation and confederation 
of 
Croats and Muslims can be set up; however, not even force can 
secure Serb participation. 
  In view of the above I think that the most logical way 
forward would be to sum up the negotiations so far, to decide if 
the Owen-Stoltenberg plan is dead, and to convene a new 
conference in which all three sides would take part and at which 
fresh proposals for territorial divisions between the three 
national communities would be submitted, Krajisnik said and went 
on to stress: 
  It is only the issue of territories that can be discussed 
realistically since we have already committed ourselves to a 
union of three independent states in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
Krajisnik said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8467 </DOCNO>
