<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ganic on Local Distrust of Russian UN Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903170294 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0903170294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina Presidency Member Ejup Ganic 
received representatives of the Russian Battalion today, which 
as a part of the UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] is carrying out 
its duties in the [Serb-held] Sarajevo district of Grbavica. 
  After welcoming them, Dr. Ganic explained the current 
situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina to the Russian UNPROFOR soldiers 
and emphasized that the Serbs are not the only ones to have the 
exclusive privilege of cooperation with Russia. The legal 
Bosnia-Herzegovina authorities want this cooperation, too. 
However, as Dr. Ganic said, very little is known in Russia 
about the events in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The Russian media do 
not have the correct information about the events on these 
territories. When the war is over, Ganic said, some politicians 
will perhaps have to answer for concealing war crimes committed 
on the territories of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The reason for today's meeting with the representative of 
the 
Russian UN Battalion was also the mistrust of citizens toward 
these soldiers, especially after seeing the television footage 
of their arrival in Pale. However, it does not seem that there 
will be any major problems. 
  The representatives of the Russian forces -- Assistant 
Commander of the Sector South (Aleksandar Mihaylovic) [word 
indistinct] and Commander of the Russian Battalion in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Victor (?Vorodilov) -- emphasized that they 
are merely a part of UNPROFOR and only accountable to the UN 
Secretary General and the UN Security Council. 

</TEXT>

