<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR Convoy Without Military Escort Blocked </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903170694 Paris AFP in English 1642 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0903170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Sarajevo, March 9 (AFP) -- A UNHCR humanitarian 
aid convoy blocked at Teslic, 30 kilometres (18 miles) from the 
north-west Bosnian town of Maglaj does not have a UN military 
escort, the UNHCR admitted Wednesday. 
  "We didn't ask UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] escort since 
it 
is not operating in this area," Peter Kessler, spokesman for the 
UN High Commission for Refugees said. 
  Asked about the UN Protection Force's mandate for protecting 
humanitarian convoys, UNPROFOR spokesman Major Jose Labandeira 
said the organisation had not agreed to force the convoy's 
passage through blockades. 
  "We don't want to use force. If we do it, they (the local 
Bosnian Serb militia) can destroy bridges and put mines on 
roads," Labandeira said. 
  Kessler said that the last UNHCR convoy which tried to get 
into Maglaj on October 26 was given a UN military escort. Two 
of the convoy's driver's were killed in the action. 
  Maglaj, which has a majority-Moslem population, has been 
under seige by Serb forces since last June. 
  UNHCR has supplied Maglaj by airdrops, some of which fell 
onto Serb lines, Kessler said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

