<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats Report Muslims Violating Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0803204094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1908 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0803204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 8 (TANJUG) -- Moslem forces on 
Tuesday fired mortar shells at a school in the Croat village of 
Uzdol near Prozor in central Bosnia. 
  Moslems thus violated the ceasefire which they had agreed 
with Croats on February 25, warned a statement by the defence 
ministry of the Bosnian Croat state of Herceg-Bosna in the 
former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Zagreb-based 
Croatian Radio said. 
  The radio also said that Moslem forces were bringing in 
reinforcements and regrouping their troops around Uskolje 
(former Gornji Vakuf) in central Bosnia. 
  Heavy clashes between local Moslems and Croats, former 
allies 
in their war against Bosnian Serbs, have been underway in 
central and southern Bosnia-Herzegovina for over a year. The 
clashes have not ceased even after the two sides agreed to form 
a Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The agreement 
was signed by representatives of Bosnian Moslems and Croats in 
Washington on March 1, under strong pressure from the United 
States. 
  Moslem forces opened strong infantry and artillery fire on 
Serb villages and positions in the area of Mt. Ozren, northern 
Bosnia, on Monday and Tuesday, Bosnian Serb military sources 
said. 
  The army of the Serb republic repulsed a Moslem combined 
artillery-infantry attack in the region of this mountain, the 
sources said. 
  Strong Moslem infantry attacks were also repulsed in the 
valley of the River Trebava and around Maglaj in northern Bosnia. 
  Moslem forces used helicopters to scout Bosnian Serb army 
positions in southern Bosnia-Herzegovina, despite the United 
Nations resolution on a no-fly zone over Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8476 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu047_i_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-047 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats Oppose Placing Mostar Under EU Control </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0903163094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1508 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0903163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 9 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Croats oppose 
the placing of Mostar under European Union (E.U.) protection, 
TANJUG on Wednesday learned from well-informed sources. 
  They are going to propose that this city in southern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina be included into the Bosnian Croat state, 
while the Moslems would get one of the Mostar municipalities, 
i.e. the section mostly Moslem-populated before the war. 
  TANJUG learned that an E.U. mission, made up of high-ranking 
Greek, German and Belgian officials, is due to arrive in Mostar 
in the next few days, with a view to determining the 
possibilities of the establishment and implementation of the 
E.U. protectorate. 
  The Serbs residing in Mostar have been excluded from the 
division. Before the war broke out in April 1992, 24,000 Serbs 
lived in Mostar, accounting for one-third of the population. 
44,000 Moslems, 43,000 Croats and 12,000 residents, who declared 
themselves as Yugoslavs, have lived in Mostar at that time. The 
E.U. protectorate would ensure the return of the Serbs, who have 
been forced to leave the city under Moslem-Croat pressure. Over 
45,000 Serbs have been expelled from Mostar and the Neretva 
valley and nearly all of their homes, churches, monasteries and 
cemeteries have been plundered, and burned and torn down. Since 
early 1993, fierce Moslem-Croat clashes have been taking place 
in central and southern Bosnia-Herzegovina, during which the 
city of Mostar has been completely destroyed. 
  Under strong pressure from the United States, 
representatives 
of the Bosnian Moslems and Croats along with Croatian 
representatives signed in Washington on March 1 a preliminary 
agreement on setting up a bi-national federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, which would subsequently enter into a 
confederation with Croatia, but the hostilities have never 
ceased. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

