<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gligorov Discusses Issues, `Greek-Serbian Axis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903175794 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0903175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Gligorov's Interview to Bulgarian </F>
Television"] 
  [Text] In his interview for the Bulgarian National 
Television, President Gligorov stated several current issues of 
the political and economic situation in the country. 
  As for the Greek demands of changes in the Macedonian [The 
Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] Constitution and 
its flag, he stressed he "had never given nor can now give 
promises" for possible changes by Macedonia, but these issues 
can be discussed in an effort to seek compromises. But, he 
said, no negotiating is possible in conditions of embargoes and 
preconditions. 
  In reference to the "Greek-Serbian" axis, Papoulias' visit 
to 
Belgrade, and the embargo that followed afterward, President 
Gligorov said he considers mutual relations between the Balkan 
countries to be their internal affairs. It is only important to 
accept Macedonia as an independent and sovereign state, whose 
existence is a condition for peace and stability in the Balkans. 
  President Gligorov does not believe that additional troops 
in 
Macedonia, whether Russian or from any other country, are 
necessary. He said present UN peace-keeping forces are 
sufficient. 
  Asked on the latest radicalization of the Serbian party in 
Macedonia, Gligorov stated he does not expect any border 
incidents (although they are not completely excluded as long as 
the war is on), because Serbs in Macedonia are given all 
possible rights. "I would be happy to see such rights for the 
Macedonians in Serbia," he added. Gligorov said the PDP [Party 
for Democratic Prosperity] split is a "normal process in a 
democratic state." The worst possible solution would be forming 
ghettos of any nationality. It is another issue what forces and 
what party option will come out as a winner. 
  Asked on Bulgarians in Macedonia, Gligorov said they have 
been given the opportunity to self-declare themselves in 
previous consensus. 
  The East-West corridor is a "priority matter" for the 
Macedonian president. Mr. Gligorov said he is personal friend 
with the Bulgarian President Zhelyu Zhelev and said Mr. Zhelev 
is a man of wide democratic views close to his own. 

</TEXT>

