<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate Rejects UDMR Amendment of Police Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903132594 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1100 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0903132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today the Senate resumed its plenary session. At 
the opening of the session, upon a proposal made by Senator 
Constantin Ticu Dumitrescu, the senators marked their regret 
over the persons who fell in the struggle against Communism by 
standing silently for a minute. Following this, they resumed 
discussing the draft bill on the organization and functioning of 
the Romanian Police. 
  An amendment proposed by the Democratic Union of Hungarians 
in Romania [UDMR] parliamentary group stirred a fierce dispute 
among the senators. Among other things, the amendment 
stipulates that, quote, in the territorial-administrative units 
in which the ethnic minority inhabitants represent the majority 
as compared to the total number of the population, the newly 
appointed or employed personnel of the police must be able to 
speak the language of that ethnic minority, respectively, must 
come, in a sufficient number, from among the persons belonging 
to that ethnic minority, unquote. 
  However, the amendment was then rejected, as merely 16 
senators voted in its favor. 
  The debate continued after a short break. The most important 
article that was discussed by the end of the morning session 
referred to the sentencing to life imprisonment of persons who 
kill police officers in the exercise of their duty. 
  Our correspondent, Victor Spirache, also reports that, after 
discussions were suspended on that draft bill, a number of 
senators made statements in their own name on various issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

