<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan Viewed as Opportunity for Serbs To Unite </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1003215894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1829 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1003215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 10 (TANJUG)--Leader of the Serbian 
Radical Party Dr Vojislav Seselj said on Thursday the Washington 
agreement on a Moslem-Croat federation had given the Serbs the 
most favourable opportunity to unify all their territories. 
  The Serbian Radical Party is the second-strongest opposition 
party in the Serbian Parliament. 
  "If Jamahiriya (Seselj's term for the Bosnian Moslem state) 
and the Bosnian-Croat Republic of Herceg-Bosna can subsequently 
enter a confederation with Croatia, who can prevent the Bosnian 
Serb Republic to join Yugoslavia," Seselj underscored at a press 
conference. According to him, Serb politicians should use this 
opportunity in the best possible way. 
  He added, however, that the Belgrade authorities had voiced 
their restraint on the issue and lacked courage to make a more 
resolved move in their foreign policy. He urged that the 
Bosnian Serb Republic and the Republic of Serb Krajina should 
merge, and consequently have one government, prime minister and 
parliament. 
  Asked about Germany's decision to expel nationals of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, mainly ethnic Albanians from 
Serbia's province of Kosovo/Metohija, Seselj said it was a way 
of putting pressure on Belgrade. He added that this problem 
could be solved at the border. 
  His solution for the problem was to deny entrance to 
Yugoslavia to all Albanians who had illegaly come to 
Kosovo/Metohija in 1948 and later, and who had not acquired 
Yugoslav citizenship. As for ethnic Albanians who had refused 
to serve their military term with the Yugoslav Army and had, 
therefore, escaped to Germany, they should immediately be 
arrested. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

