<H3> <TI>   Explain Alliance Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1003214294 Paris AFP in English 2122 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1003214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Zagreb, March 10 (AFP)--Bosnian Croats said 
Thursday they would not accept a federation with Moslems in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina which was not linked to a confederation with 
Croatia proper. [passage omitted] 
  The statement was issued here after the presidential council 
of the republic of Hereg-Bosna met in Mostar, southern Bosnia 
[location as received]. 
  The council has 11 members and is chaired by Kresimir Zubak, 
who has also headed the Bosnian Croat delegation in Vienna at 
talks on the proposed Moslem-Croat federation, brokered in 
Washington last week. 
  The council expressed its "full support" for its delegation 
in Vienna, but said that it had an "obligation to coordinate 
daily with the members of the presidential council who are not 
part of the delegation." 
  The report came after Zagreb's deputy foreign minister Ivo 
Sanader said that the talks in Vienna could be concluded Friday 
with leaders from both sides flying in to work out the final 
details. 
  Further discussions would be needed on the "demarcation of 
the Croat and Moslem cantons" in the future federation. [passage 
omitted] 
  Croatian President Franjo Tudjman said on Monday that the 
question of a confederation would be put to a referendum in the 
republic, but added that the issue could not be settled "so long 
as the question of Serbs in Bosnia-Herzegovina remains 
unresolved." 

</TEXT>

