<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Convoys Ready To Enter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103130794 Paris AFP in English 1240 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103130794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 11 (AFP)--The UN High Commissioner 
for Refugees (UNHCR) is readying two aid convoys for Bosnia's 
besieged Maglaj region which has been cut off for nine months by 
Serb forces, UNHCR spokesman Peter Kessler said Friday. 
  The Bosnian Serbs Thursday again prevented one 10-truck 
convoy carrying 92 tons of food from entering the northern town, 
forcing the UNHCR to divert it to Zenica, in central Bosnia. 
  Kessler said the UNHCR's head of operations in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Larry Hollingworth, who accompanied the 
convoy, was splitting it into two, one for Maglaj itself and one 
for the town of Tesanj, 15 kilometres (10 miles) west. 
  The two towns are in the Maglaj pocket, containing some 
130,000 people who have been under siege by the Serbs since last 
June. They are only supplied by international air drops and 
latest reports speak of desperate conditions in the area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

