<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Commitment Urged </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103115594 Paris AFP in English 1144 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, March 11 (AFP)--Negotiations on forming a 
federation of Bosnian Moslems and Croats look set to stretch 
into next week, Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic said 
Friday after meeting with Austrian President Thomas Klestil. 
  "They will not end today," the premier said, adding that he 
expected to spend the whole of the weekend in Vienna. "I do not 
think we are in any hurry," he said. "We have to pay attention 
to each detail. It is serious work." 
  The US-sponsored talks were scheduled to work out the 
details 
of an agreement reached earlier this month in Washington to set 
up a Croat-Moslem federation in Bosnia-Hercegovina. 
  The talks were complicated by a decision by Bosnian Croat 
leaders inside Bosnia on Wednesday to insist that the 
Moslem-Croat entity be formally linked in a confederation with 
neighbouring Croatia. 
  Silajdzic said he had talks scheduled for Friday evening 
with 
Croatia's Foreign Minister Mate Granic. 
  He said Serbs would be invited to take part in a joint 
effort 
to find a negotiated settlement to continued fighting between 
their forces and the Moslem-led Bosnian army, even though the 
Serbs have so far refused. 
  "Certain relations with the Serbs of Serbia and the Serbs of 
Bosnia will have to be discussed," he said. 
  Silajdzic noted that Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
had assured him during a meeting earlier this week in Moscow 
that Russia would do its best to bring the Serbs into a 
negotiated final solution. 
  There was a chance of reaching agreement in Vienna if there 
is "enough goodwill and if our friends, in particular the United 
States, maintain their current commitment," Silajdzic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8525 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu048aa_94003" </HT>


