<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Signs Partnership for Peace Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1003173494 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1003173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by special correspondent Miroslav Konvalina] </F>
  [Excerpts] Brussels--Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus is 
at this very moment signing the Partnership for Peace project, 
which offers postcommunist countries cooperation in security and 
political issues. The Czech Republic has become the 11th country 
to join the project. [passage omitted] 
  Klaus said in his speech that the Czech Republic regards the 
Partnership for Peace as a brave initiative that means a new 
stage in our relations with NATO, the military and political 
organization of 16 countries that we are striving to join. 
  As far as our admission into the European Union is 
concerned, 
Klaus was, in his own words, very optimistic following his talks 
with the EU Commission President Jacques Delors, in particular 
when he said that the end or the turn of the century was too 
late for us as a date for our admission as a fully fledged 
member. The Czech prime minister shocked the Hungarians and the 
Poles, in particular, with this statement. They are expecting 
to be admitted to the alliance at the turn of the century. 
  Neither Delors nor Klaus regard it as decisive when a 
country 
submits an application for full membership in the Twelve. What 
is more important is when they meet the specific qualitative 
criteria for membership set by the Maastricht Treaty. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

