<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poland To Abstain From Human Rights Vote </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1003193094 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1800 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1003193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MSZ] has instructed 
the Polish delegate of the UN Human Rights Commission to abstain 
from voting on the resolution condemning transgressions of human 
and civil rights in China. Sladyslaw Klaczynski, the director 
of the MSZ press department, explained that Poland did not 
condemn the transgression of human rights in China since it is 
difficult to conscientiously judge the situation by virtue of 
the distance between our countries. Director Jan Woroniecki of 
the UN department [of the MSZ] informed us that the MSZ had 
instructed the Human Rights Commission's Polish delegate to 
abstain from voting after consultations with the government. 
  In turn, Justice Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz stated 
that 
the stance of the MSZ on this matter is not the stance of the 
government, but merely an internal instruction of the MSZ, one 
with which he is not familiar. The Democratic Union and the 
Liberal Democratic Congress have expressed indignation on 
account of the nongranting by Poland of support for the UN 
resolution on the transgression of human rights in China. Union 
of Labor Deputy Aleksander Malachowski said that this decision 
is an example of the victory of trade and economic interests 
over a feeling of responsibility for adherence to elementary 
civil rights. 
  Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the special delegate of the UN Human 
Rights Commission in the former Yugoslavia, said that the 
sacrifice of higher criteria, as he termed the protection of 
human rights, for other political criteria threatens the state 
with a loss of respect in the world. On the other hand, in the 
view of Krzysztof Krol of the Confederation for Independent 
Poland, the decision of the Polish Government on the issue of 
the voting was correct and witnesses to the independence of 
Polish foreign policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

