<H3> <TI>   Second Serbian Submarine Sighted in Adriatic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003160594 The Hague ANP in Dutch 1739 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BR1003160594 </F>
<F P=104>  The Hague ANP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Second Serbian Submarine Sighted in </F>
Adriatic Sea"; as released by The Hague ANP Database] 
  [Text] The Hague, 8 Mar (ANP) -- Western naval ships have 
observed a second Serbian submarine in the Adriatic Sea. It was 
already known that a Heroj-class submarine, the "Uskok," had 
already sailed. Now, however, a Sava-class submarine has also 
been observed, a navy spokesman confirmed. Each boat can be 
fitted out with 10 torpedoes. 
  Western ships are patrolling the Adriatic Sea in order to 
supervise the UN oil and arms embargo against the former 
Yugoslavia. The Netherlands ships serving there are the "Jacob 
van Heemskerck" and the "Van Kinsbergen." 
  The Adriatic Sea is not a no-go area for submarines from 
Serbia and Montenegro, the navy spokesman said. He did say, 
however, that it was interesting that a second submarine was 
operational. 

</TEXT>

