<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unit To Protect Serbian Enclave </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1003204094 Prague CTK in English 1941 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1003204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 10 (CTK) -- One hundred and twenty 
troops forming the Czech UNPROFOR [United Nations Protection 
Force] unit will be deployed in the Croatian area of Zepce north 
of Sarajevo, the Czech defense minister said on Thursday. 
  Speaking at a meeting of the parliamentary foreign committee 
discussing the situation in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Antonin 
Baudys said the transport will take place on March 15. 
  Asked whether the soldiers knew they were going to protect a 
Serbian enclave surrounded by Bosnian Muslims, Baudys said all 
of the soldiers volunteered for inclusion in the unit. They 
will be equipped with submachine guns and bulletproof vests and 
will use 14 armored personnel carriers, 11 trucks, five "special 
trailers" and one ambulance. 
  UNPROFOR command has not yet announced how long the unit, 
which is to operate within a Jordanian regiment, would be 
stationed in Croatia. [as received] 
  The Czech government approved the consignment on Wednesday 
[9 
March]. 

</TEXT>

