<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus on Russian Interest in `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0903200094 Prague CTK in English 1746 GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0903200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 9 (CTK) -- The Czech Republic does 
not look at the Partnership for Peace proposal "in any different 
way" now Russia has expressed interest in the plan, Czech 
Premier Vaclav Klaus told journalists on Wednesday [9 March]. 
  Russia announced its interest in joining on February 28 
after 
consultation with NATO experts. 
  The Czech Republic respects the plan, Klaus said, adding 
that 
"our sole task is, along with NATO's member states, to fill the 
plan with something of substance." 
  "We understand the Partnership for Peace unambiguously as a 
mechanism of our strategical aim, which is the admission of the 
Czech Republic to NATO," he said. 
  Klaus is to sign a general agreement on Czech participation 
in the scheme in Brussels on Thursday. 
  The programme was approved at the NATO summit in Brussels on 
January 10-11 this year. Since then Slovakia, Poland, Hungary, 
Romania, Bulgaria, Albania, Ukraine, Lithuania, Latvia and 
Estonia have added their signatures to the project. 

</TEXT>

