<H3> <TI>   Kovac Confirms Parties Supported Him </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103201894 Prague CTK in English 1946 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 11 (CTK) -- Former Deputy Premier 
Roman Kovac confirmed to CTK today that several parties had 
proposed he become the new Slovak premier. 
  The governing Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) will 
"almost certainly" be addressed when the new government is 
formed, said Kovac, who was recently expelled from the HZDS 
following his criticism of former Premier Vladimir Meciar. The 
composition of the government will be decided within a week, he 
added. 
  Leader of the Christian Democratic Movement (KDH) Jan 
Carnogursky called September the most likely election date. "I 
hope parliament will pass the constitutional law setting the 
date for early elections in the autumn," he added. 
  Carnogursky ruled out the possibility that he would join the 
new government, adding that the idea that the cabinet be formed 
without political leaders was correct. 
  "A new cabinet can be formed within a few hours," former 
chairman of the Slovak National Party Ludovit Cernak said. "All 
the parties are ready to put an end to feuds and to agree on a 
broad coalition government which will lead Slovakia to early 
elections," he said. 
  "I believe ethnic Hungarian parties will not make 
extravagant 
claims because all the parties have pledged to set their own 
needs aside," Cernak said. He confirmed he respected the 
preliminary agreement providing for the absence of political 
leaders in the provisional government. 

</TEXT>

