<H3> <TI>   Speech Called `Gross Insult' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1003204294 Prague CTK in English 1859 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1003204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kosice, East Slovakia, March 10 (CTK) -- The speech 
given by Slovak President Michal Kovac on Wednesday is a "gross 
insult to parliamentary democracy," says a statement passed at a 
Thursday meeting of heads of district authorities. 
  Seventeen district heads and two government commissioners 
signed the document, also saying that Kovac's "reckless and 
false accusations" of Premier Vladimir Meciar and some members 
of the government "cannot be described as being other than an 
expedient aimed at destabilizing political situation and 
discrediting the government." 
  They said that Kovac's "attacks" addressed to State 
Secretary 
of the Privatization Ministry Ivan Lexa were a show of "vanity 
incompatible with the post held by Michal Kovac," and that in 
this way, Kovac detracts from the weight of his office. 
  The statement says that Kovac is playing into the hands of 
the forces which lost in the elections, were against the Slovak 
independence and work for its destruction. 

</TEXT>

