<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Makes Allegations Against Kovac </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103175894 Prague CTK in English 1702 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 11 (CTK) -- In his speech to 
parliament before his resignation, Premier Vladimir Meciar 
denied President Michal Kovac's accusation that he had 
conditioned appointment of Ivan Lexa as privatization minister 
on to the procurement of money for the ruling HZDS (Movement for 
a Democratic Slovakia). 
  Even if the talks took place and were true, there is an 
unwritten rule that they are never talked about, claimed Meciar. 
  Meciar said that former Foreign Minister Milan Knazko had to 
travel to Croatia on Meciar's order to withdraw Kovac's promise 
of cooperation in arms production. 
  Kovac allegedly sent a letter to Taiwan promising to 
recognize it if Slovakia received $500 million. "This would 
cause an immediate political conflict with China. We were 
essentially opposed to it," Meciar said. 
  After the first talks with Czech President Vaclav Havel, 
Kovac requested that the Slovak government pay 18.2 billion 
Slovak crowns [Sk] ($550 million) for the National Property Fund 
(FNM) and Sk24 billion ($800 million) for the Czech deficit. "I 
disagreed with the request, and the shares worth Sk178.2 billion 
($5,400 million) eventually arrived in Slovakia gratis," Meciar 
added. 
  The meeting between the Slovak delegation and American 
President Bill Clinton, which was preceded by careful 
preparations, was a wasted opportunity, Meciar said. The talks 
with Clinton were a historic chance for Slovakia to resolve its 
security and economic interests. 
  Meciar said he had not had a chance to speak because Kovac 
delivered a 34-minute speech. The American party reacted 
negatively, as well. "I felt ashamed," Meciar commented on the 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

