<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Addresses Polish National Front </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1203142494 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1105 
GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1203142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We want this to become the beginning of our 
relations between Russia and Poland, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, 
leader of the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia [LDPR], said 
about his visit to Poland. 
  [Andrzej Kruszynski] Speaking at the deliberations of the 
Self-Defense National Front, at whose leader's, Janusz 
Bryczkowski's, invitation Zhirinovskiy came to Poland, the 
Russian politician sent a message to Polish politicians saying 
that Poland can have in Russia a real help in the implementation 
of its national interests. Denying all interference in the 
internal affairs of our country, the main body of Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy's address was aimed at convincing the Poles about 
the benefits ensuing from close economic and political ties of 
the whole Slavonic commonwealth, not excluding a military 
treaty. Such a commonwealth can become the greatest power in 
the world, the Russian politician added. 
  There were also anti-Western accents in his address. In 
Zhirinovskiy's opinion, the West would be happy to see enmity 
amongst the Slavs. This is Andrzej Kruszynski speaking for the 
First Program of Polish Radio. 

</TEXT>

