<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visits Grunwald Battlefield </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303163894 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1538 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1303163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 13 Mar--On Sunday, the second day of 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy's visit to Poland, the leader of the 
Liberal Democratic Party of Russia went to visit the Grunwald 
battlefields (Olsztyn province), where he laid flowers in front 
of the Grunwald monument. He was accompanied by Janusz 
Bryczkowski, chairman of the Polish National Front. 
  "I am laying flowers on the soil where for centuries 
Germans, 
Poles, and Russians fought battles. Grunwald was a joint 
Polish-Russian victory," Zhirinovskiy said, pointing out that 
Smolensk battalions took part in the battle. 
  When asked by journalists to whom the former East Prussia 
should belong, Zhirinovksiy said that "the borders were 
determined 50 years ago as a result of blood shed by Polish and 
Russian soldiers, and these territories belong to Poland." 
  Zhirinovskiy said that there is enough room "along the 
Baltic 
for everyone--the Germans, the Poles, and the Russians." 
  This morning, before his departure for Olsztyn province, 
Zhirinovskiy took a walk in Warsaw's Lazienki Park and the 
Castle Square. Together with Janusz Bryczkowski, he laid 
flowers in front of the Warsaw Uprising monument. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

