<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   First UN Military Observers Arrive in Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1303193194 Paris AFP in English 1930 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1303193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 13 (AFP)--Two teams of 10 UN 
military observers each arrived Sunday evening [13 March] in the 
besieged Moslem enclave of Maglaj, a United Nations Protection 
Force (UNPROFOR) spokesman said. 
  Their arrival marks the first time the United Nations has 
had 
a presence in this Moslem enclave, which has been besieged by 
Bosnian Serb forces since last June, said spokesman Major Rob 
Annink. The spokesman did not provide further details. 
  UN officials have been unable to confirm reports of the 
latest round of fighting in Maglaj as there have been no 
international observers there. 
  In addition, UN humanitarian aid has been blocked from 
Maglaj 
since October. Western concern has grown about Maglaj as Serb 
attacks are continuing there despite ceasefires in Sarajevo and 
central and southern Bosnia. 
  A UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) convoy was 
refused passage into Maglaj last week by Serb troops. 
  UNHCR officials have said the situation in Maglaj is 
desperate, with attacks mounting on the 16,000 people in the 
town since Serbs and Moslems reached a ceasefire in Sarajevo 
February 11 and since a Moslem-Croat ceasefire in central and 
southern Bosnia came into effect on February 28. 
  Radio Sarajevo reported that Serb forces began as of 5:30 
A.M. Sunday (0430 GMT) artillery and mortar attacks on the 
enclave that lasted for two hours. There was then sporadic 
mortar fire. Two people were wounded, it said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

