<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Muslim-Serb Disengagement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303184194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1822 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1303184194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Mar 13 (TANJUG)--Military disengagement 
between Bosnian Moslems and Serbs could start in Maglaj, town in 
northern Bosnia, the special Russian envoy to the former 
Yugoslavia Vitaliy Churkin said Sunday. 
  Churkin said he had discussed Sunday in Sarajevo with 
Bosnian 
Moslem Leader Alija Izetbegovic the possibility of taking 
advantage of the recent positive developments between Moslems 
and Croats to apply the experience also between Moslems and 
Serbs to get them to disengage their forces and perhaps place 
heavy weapons under control, FRANCE PRESSE reports. 
  Serbs, Moslems and Croats have been waging a bitter war in 
the former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina since April 
1992. With U.S. mediation, Bosnian Moslems and Croats signed an 
agreement in Washington earlier this month on forming a 
federation in Bosnia- Herzegovina which would later form a 
confederation with neighbouring Croatia, also a former Yugoslav 
republic. 
  The possibility of the third warring party joining the 
federation remains open. 
  After signing the Washington agreement, Croat and Moslem 
military representatives ratified it Saturday in Split and 
signed a document on the formation of a joint army. 
  According to a UPI report, after a one-hour talk with 
Izetbegovic, Churkin pointed out that Sarajevo must remain 
undivided. 
  Bosnian Serbs and Moslems, he said, must put aside their 
political differences and start working on restoring 
electricity, running water, transportation and other services in 
Sarajevo. 
  According to Churkin, the federation between Bosnian Croats 
and Moslems is not necessarily contrary to Bosnian Serb 
interests and could be a useful element of the overall 
settlement of the Bosnian conflict. 
  According to FRANCE PRESSE, Churkin is due to meet Bosnian 
Serb Leader Radovan Karadzic later in the day. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8618 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu049_i_94005" </HT>


