<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik Reviews Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303205794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2011 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1303205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 13 Mar (TANJUG)--Momcilo Krajisnik, 
president of the Srpska republic's people's assembly, has said 
the Serbs have no reason to join with Croats and Muslims nor to 
allow anyone to deny them the right to join with the Serbs from 
other republics. 
  Krajisnik said this after talks in Pale today with the 
Russian president's special envoy Vitaliy Churkin, which took 
place after Churkin's talks with Muslim President Alija 
Izetbegovic in Sarajevo. 
  "Churkin came here to inform us about the talks he held with 
the Muslim side and about the talks between the Croats and 
Muslims. He wanted to hear our position on this," Krajisnik 
said after the talks with Churkin. 
  "Churkin said no obstacles should be put in the way of the 
Croat-Muslim agreement. He also said that some people think 
that the Serbs should also have a loose link with the 
Croat-Muslim federation, perhaps in the form of a union," 
Krajisnik said. 
  He added that he had told Churkin that the Serb side's 
position will be officially presented tomorrow in Belgrade, 
where Churkin is expected to meet Nikola Koljevic, the Srpska 
republic's deputy president, and Aleksa Buha, the foreign 
minister. 
  "Churkin told me the Bosnian Serbs should have a firmer link 
with the rest of the Serb people," Krajisnik said, and added 
that the Russian envoy did not define the nature of such a link 
in clear terms. "The concept is not exactly clear, but we have 
nevertheless undertaken the obligation to negotiate all possible 
solutions," Krajisnik said, adding that the Serb side is ready 
to resume talks as long as Serb interests are not threatened. 
  As regards Churkin's statement after the talks with 
Izetbegovic that Tuzla airport will not be under the control of 
Russian troops but that the Russian military observers will be 
deployed there, Krajisnik said: "We reached an agreement on 
this in Russia. According to the agreement, civilian Russian 
representatives will be deployed at Tuzla airport, together with 
the Serb ones. I think this is a realistic agreement, and Mr. 
Churkin said today the Russian side will insist on it. This 
gives us encouragement in our belief that we will finally reach 
the right solution for the opening of Tuzla airport," Krajisnik 
said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8619 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu049_i_94006" </HT>


