<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mladic Objects to French UN Troop Deployment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1303002694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2322 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1303002694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 12 Mar (TANJUG)--The commander of the army 
of the Srpska republic, Gen. Ratko Mladic, this evening warned 
the head of the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] mission for 
former Yugoslavia, Yasushi Akashi, that problematic actions by 
members of the French UN battalion deployed in the region of 
Bihac could lead to undesirable incidents. 
  In a letter to Akashi, Gen. Mladic stresses that the French 
UN battalion has deployed its reconaissance groups in front of 
the Muslim forces along the lines of separation facing the Serb 
units. 
  "Thus deployed UNPROFOR reconaissance groups have been used 
by the Muslim forces as a safe position from where they can open 
fire against positions held by the army of the Srpska republic. 
At the same time, they wish to trigger our retaliation against 
the UNPROFOR members, by which they would cause a conflict 
between the Serb forces and UNPROFOR," says Gen. Mladic's letter 
which was forwarded to TANJUG. 
  The commander of the army of the Srpska republic assesses 
that this deployment of the reconnaissance groups by the French 
battalion is "objectively speaking benefiting the protection of 
the Muslim forces and tolerating combat activities from thier 
positions and adjacent to them; this could force a reaction by 
our forces in terms of self-defense and cause more serious 
consequences." 
  Gen. Mladic recalls in his letter to Akashi that "hitherto 
not one member of the UNPROFOR forces has been killed by our 
forces, and other unpleasant situations are extremely rare," and 
he requests that the head of the UNPROFOR mission personally 
take it upon himself to see to it that the French reconnaissance 
groups are removed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8622 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu049_i_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-049 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Serbs Agree To Open Roads, Bridge </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1203193594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1203193594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Negotiations with the Serb aggressor side 
continued at Sarajevo Airport today. The talks were conducted by 
Hasan Muratovic, Bosnia-Herzegovina minister without portfolio, 
who came from the airport a few minutes ago and made the 
following statement for Bosnia-Herzegovina Radio: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] Mr. 
Muratovic, 
two days ago you had a meeting at which you agreed to resume the 
talks today. What was agreed today? 
  [Muratovic] Today we agreed something that we could not do 
last time. In brief, we agreed to sign an agreement by Tuesday. 
The details of it, according to our guidelines and minutes from 
the meeting, will be worked out by UNPROFOR [UN Protection 
Forces]. The details include maps showing roads. 
  We have agreed to open up the Butmir-Dobrinja road--which 
will run across the airport runway--for our use, and the 
Lukavica-Ilidza road--which will also run across the airport 
runway--for use by the Serbian side. The roads will cut across 
each other at one point. We have also agreed to open up the 
Sarajevo-Visoko road via Vogosca, and to open the Grbavica 
bridge for civilians. 
  All this will be opened up simultaneously on Saturday, 18 
March, if the agreement is signed, which I no longer doubt will 
happen. Only UNPROFOR can now make some problems in this 
respect, as the roads run across the airport runway. [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

