<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croat, Muslim Groups Sign U.S.-Brokered Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1203125094 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1203125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After three days of very intensive talks and work on 
the coordination of positions, the military representatives of 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government and the Croatian Defense 
Council [HVO], Generals Rasim Delic and Ante Roso, signed a 
document on accepting certain principles for the implementation 
of military agreements as an obligation stemming from the 
general agreement in Washington. The document was signed at the 
Villa Dalmacija in Split in the presence of U.S. 
mediator-ambassador Jack Galvin. By signing the document, the 
military leaders of the Croat and Muslim sides in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina accepted and strongly upheld the earlier 
peace agreement concluded through UNPROFOR's [UN Protection 
Forces] mediation and accepted certain tasks concerning the 
organization of the federal army of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The signing of this document by the military delegations of 
the HVO and the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army was described by U.S. 
mediator Jack Galvin as historic. Galvin paid tribute to both 
sides for their support and readiness to implement the document 
in its entirety. The cease-fire process, as U.S. mediator Galvin 
said in a statement for the public, has taken off successfully 
in the field and is even being implemented beyond all 
expectations. This initial step and today's signing of the 
document by the military commanders of the HVO and the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army are also important because they prove to 
the United States that the agreement signed in Washington was 
something acceptable to both sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-8624 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu049_i_94011" </HT>


