<H3> <TI>   Muslim-Croat Fighting Continuing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1203182094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1739 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1203182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, Mar 12 (TANJUG)--Moslem-Croat fighting 
in the central and southwest parts of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
continues despite an agreement, signed on Saturday, on forming a 
joint Croat-Moslem army. 
  The radio of the Bosnian Croat state of Herceg-Bosna said on 
Saturday that Moslem forces in the region of Kiseljak, Kresevo 
and [word indistinct] continue violating the ceasefire agreement 
by opening mortar and infantry fire on Croat positions. 
  The radio said that the situation in the other Moslem-Croat 
fronts was somewhat quieter but that the Moslem army continues 
reinforcing its positions, regrouping and bringing in fresh 
troops. 
  The Zagreb-based Croatian radio, however, said that on 
Saturday afternoon the Croat part of the Herzegovina city of 
Mostar was hit by a shell fired from the Moslem positions, after 
which a general alert was sounded. 
  Moslem Sarajevo radio claims that Croat snipers in Mostar 
continue firing on the separation line and civilian facilties in 
the Moslem-controlled part of the city. 
  According to the radio, in the southern parts of Mostar, the 
Croats are torching the remaining Moslem homes to prevent their 
owners from returning. 
  The Bosnian Moslems and Croats, who have been fiercly 
clashing in central and southwest Bosnia since last spring, are 
continuing their battles despite a draft agreement on a 
Moslem-Croat federation in this ex-Yugoslav republic which was 
signed early this month in Washington under strong U.S. pressure. 
  The military part of this agreement was on Saturday signed 
by 
the commanders of the Moslem and Croat forces, Rasim Delic and 
Ante Roso. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

