<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hurried Ethnic Cleansing Before Agreement Signed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1103231394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2030 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1103231394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, March 11 (TANJUG)--Bosnian Croat and 
Moslem authorities are rushing to ethnically cleanse the 
territories under their control before reaching final agreement 
on a Croat-Moslem federation in war-shattered 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bosnian Serb army sources said on Friday. 
  The Croat-populated village of Lovrici near Gradacac in the 
north has been completely depopulated, which the Moslem media 
are trying to deny. 
  Also, Croats in Zenica, central Bosnia, are selling out 
their 
property at a frenzied rate, a sure sign of preparations for a 
move-out. 
  Moslem authorities have ordered the torching of Croat houses 
in the abandoned village of Zubici near Travnik, also in central 
Bosnia, and the two sides are trading accusations of burning and 
demolishing houses around Mostar in the south. 
  On the Kiseljak front near Sarajevo on Friday, Moslem 
infantry forces attacked Croat positions at the locality of 
Kazagici in an effort to break into Croat-held territory, said 
Zagreb-based Croatian radio. 
  The Croat troops fought back and repulsed the attack at no 
casualties to themselves, the source said. 
  The Croatian radio correspondent in Mostar said on Friday 
that the exchange of prisoners, in the course of which Croats 
held in Bugojno, central Bosnia, and Moslem-controlled east 
Mostar should be released, "is not going well." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

