<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslim-Serb `Row' Delays Tuzla Airport Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1103165494 Paris AFP in English 1637 GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1103165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, March 11 (AFP)--A row over the presence of 
Serb liaison officers to monitor aid deliveries is delaying the 
opening of Tuzla airport to relief flights, UN special envoy to 
ex-Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi said Friday [11 March]. 
  It was "premature" to talk of an agreement in Moscow between 
Russia and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic to re-open the 
airport, Akashi said. 
  The Serbs were insisting on liaison officers at the airport, 
a move vigorously opposed by the Moslem-led Bosnian government. 
  "The positions are quite apart," Akashi admitted. 
  Aid officials said the opening of the airport to 
humanitarian 
aid flights is vital to the 700,000 mainly Moslem inhabitants in 
the region who have been kept without adequate food since war 
broke out in Bosnia almost two years ago. 
  Nevertheless the UN is pressing ahead with work to ready the 
runway and airport to receive fixed winged aircraft within a 
week or two, Akashi said. 
  "We would like to do it with the agreement of the parties so 
that the airport will not be exposed to shelling or 
bombardment," he added. 
  When the airport does re-open, the humanitarian air bridge 
would fly in one or two flights per day, in daylight hours. 
  In a sign of some progress in the region, Ron Redmond, 
spokesman for the office of the UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees, said aid distribution across Bosnia last week had been 
"extremely good," with 8,100 tonnes of aid delivered in the week 
to early Friday, some 83 percent of the target. 
  However, the UNHCR had protested to the Serbs over their 
blockade of convoys for the Moslem-held pockets of Maglaj and 
Tesanj, he added. 
  A fuel convoy was allowed into Gorazde where people have 
been 
dying in hospital because its electricity generator lacked fuel. 
  However the situation at Maglaj remained very serious with 
10 
aid trucks packed with supplies forced to return to Zagreb and 
Banja Luka, Redmond said. 
  "We will attempt to send two convoys at the start of next 
week from Zagreb and Zenica and will try also to reach Tesanj," 
the UNHCR spokesman said. 
  Although Redmond said the UNHCR had protested strongly to 
the 
Serbs over the delays, Akashi blamed "Croat populations from 
neighbouring villages" for blocking the convoys. 
  The Japanese diplomat said that at a meeting with the three 
warring parties in the Bosnian conflict in Geneva on Thursday he 
had sensed "isolation, some bitterness and hardening" of the 
Serb position over a U.S.-sponsored plan for a Moslem-Croat 
federation in Bosnia. 
  On the Bosnian capital Sarajevo, Akashi said "total freedom 
of movement should be possible within the next several weeks," 
but said further negotiations were needed with the Bosnian 
government and the Serb side. 
  UN Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali is expected to 
address the UN Security Council in the next few days to say 
which countries would be invited to send contingents to the UN 
Protection Force in Bosnia, Akashi said. 
  The UN chief said 10,000 extra troops would be needed to 
maintain the "still fragile" ceasefire in Bosnia. 
  Meanwhile, the UN Protection Force successfully rotated 
Canadian troops in the eastern Moslem enclave of Srebrenica with 
their Dutch counterparts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

