<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Changes Planned for Muslim Leadership in Tuzla </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1403141594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1240 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1403141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Banja Luka, Belgrade, March 14 (TANJUG)--The 
political and military Bosnian Muslim leadership is preparing to 
make changes in the leadership of the Muslim region of Tuzla, in 
north Bosnia, dissatisfied by the moderate position and growing 
resistance of the local authorities to the continuation of war, 
it has been learnt from informed Serbian military sources. 
  The Muslim leadership does not like the policy pursued by 
the 
leadership of the Tuzla municipality, since it affects also the 
different trends and political divisions in the Muslim 
leadership in Sarajevo, and blunts the fighting fervor against 
Serbs. 
  In accordance with the radical policy of Muslim leader Alia 
Izetbegovic, new orders for mobilization have been issued in the 
Tuzla region in order to continue the offensive on Serbian 
positions towards Brcko and east of Tuzla towards Doboj, Trebava 
and Podrinja, a region under Serbian control in Bosnia. 
  Izetbegovic ordered last week his forces to capture Doboj 
and 
its surroundings, whatever the cost. 
  In the last few days, Muslim units have been reinforced to 
launch an offensive on Serbian sttlements and positions on the 
Mountain Majevica, east of Tuzla. 
  The brigade was reinforced by the so-called Sarajevo Muslim 
Army Corps, whose forces have been transferred from central 
Bosnia following the signing of the accord with Croats and the 
placing of heavy weaponry around Sarajevo under U.N. control. 

</TEXT>

