<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Australia's Decision on Names Protested </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403130394 Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA in Macedonian 14 Mar 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje NOVA MAKEDONIJA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Macedonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Basic Human Rights Violated"] </F>
  [Text] The Macedonian [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia--FYROM] Foreign Ministry expresses the concern and 
bitterness of itself and the Macedonian public about the latest 
agency reports that the Australian Government is preparing to 
implement the decision to name the Macedonian community living 
in Australia as "Slav-Macedonian." 
  The Macedonian Government does not intend to interfere in 
the 
internal affairs of any country, and in this case Australia, but 
it feels the need to emphasize that by such an act the 
Australian Government is violating the basic human rights of 
loyal Australian citizens of Macedonian origin. By that act, 
with the force of law, solutions are being imposed that are the 
opposite of the generally accepted and successfully implemented 
multinational policy of Australia, thus directly transferring 
the misunderstandings and conflicts from the Balkans to the 
decades-long peaceful multicultural milieu of Australia. It is 
hard to understand that, with an legal act of the Australian 
Government, the positive practice of Australia in this field is 
being violated. That practice was, with its results, an example 
of solving the multinational questions not only on the 
Australian continent, but at large. Those positive experiences 
have been studied and supported with great sympathy by the 
Republic of Macedonia. 
  After the recent violent terrorist acts against the 
buildings 
of the Macedonian Orthodox Church and the Macedonian community 
in Australia, which caught the attention of the world's public, 
the Macedonian Foreign Ministry officially drew the Australian 
side's attention to the unacceptable reasons for such terrorist 
activities and the possible consequences, and requested urgent 
action by the Australian state in detecting and punishing those 
who endanger the order and peace of the prosperous multicultural 
Australian society. 
<H5>  [Box, p 1] </H5>
<H5>  Protest of the Macedonians in Australia </H5>
  Sydney, 13 March--According to the announcements of the SBS 
Radio Broadcast in the Macedonian language, the Federal 
Government has ordered all its institutions to refer to the 
Macedonians as Slav Macedonians in the future. The Macedonian 
community reacted strongly to this decision, and Chris Popov, 
Goce Stefanovski, as well as some other influential 
personalities in television stated that "if Australia does not 
change this incomprehensible decision, the Macedonians will 
embark on mass demonstrations...." 
  -- T.B. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

