<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crew Questioned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1403124894 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1200 
GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1403124894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the Vidin Regional Directorate of Internal 
Affairs, investigators of the National Investigation Service are 
now questioning the 21 persons found on board the ship Khan 
Kubrat and held under arrest. An official source from the Vidin 
police announced this at a news conference today. Following 
questioning, 18 of the 21 persons were released. The three 
remaining in custody for further questioning are the ship's 
captain Kostadin Stoyanov, 39, from Ruse; the captain's first 
mate, Atanas Denchev, also from Ruse; and the engineer, Dimitur 
Krumov. 
  The only woman found on board was the wife of one of the 
members of the crew and holds a seaman's passport, Nikolay 
Dechev, chief of the Vidin police, announced at the news 
conference. In my personal opinion, the story of the hijacking 
of the Khan Kubrat by armed persons is a put-on, he added. The 
regional police chief said that the entire operation of 
detaining the vessel at 1500 on 13 March was carried out 
superbly and that the organization had worked perfectly. 
  The National Investigation Service opened an investigation 
into the case on 8 March, and its investigations will extend to 
several regions: Vidin, Pleven, Blagoevgrad, and Ruse. Nikolay 
Dechev believes that the investigation into the Khan Kubrat 
incident will be concluded fairly soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

